{# Chapter 1 — January to April #}
<div class="chapter-marker wrapped-section">
    <p class="chapter-label">Chapter 1</p>
    <h2>January &ndash; April</h2>
</div>

<section class="wrapped-section">
    <p>I didn't start 2025 with a clear plan.</p>
    <p>I started it with curiosity.</p>
    <p>The goal for the first few months was simple &mdash; <strong>do as much as possible</strong>. Build things. Try ideas. Learn aggressively. Make mistakes early while the stakes were still low.</p>

    <h3>Optimizing for Learning</h3>
    <p>January to April was a period of experimentation. I explored new programming languages, including <strong>C#</strong>, not because I needed them immediately, but because I wanted to expand how I think about software. Different languages force different mental models, and I was intentionally collecting those perspectives.</p>
    <p>At the same time, I started exploring side hustles and freelancing &mdash; mainly to understand whether it was a viable path locally.</p>
    <p>That experiment didn't last long.</p>

    <h3>A Sobering Reality Check</h3>
    <p>Trying to freelance in Zimbabwe was disappointing. I quickly noticed how undervalued software work often is. Extremely low pricing. Cut corners. Rushed deliveries.</p>
    <p>After serving just one client, I made the decision to step away. Not because I couldn't compete &mdash; but because I wasn't willing to compromise my standards or reduce my work to fit a broken market.</p>

    <h3>A Better Direction</h3>
    <p>Not long after, I joined the <a href="https://www.codementor.io/projects/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Codementor DevProjects Challenge</a> &mdash; themed <a href="https://www.codementor.io/projects/web/create-a-fast-and-secure-blog-using-jamstack-c93coupnxb" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">"Create a fast and secure blog using JAMstack."</a></p>
    <p>Instead of building for clients, I started building for myself. I created a personal blog &mdash; a space to learn in public and think out loud.</p>

    <h3>March: Hackathon Season</h3>
    <p>March changed the pace completely. My school hosted two hackathons &mdash; one focused on fintech and the other on agritech. I formed and led teams for both.</p>
    <p><strong>Fintech Hackathon:</strong> We built a peer-to-peer money transfer system using NFC. We had a working prototype. We won <strong>first place</strong> and a <strong>$1,000 cash prize</strong>.</p>

    <div align="center" style="margin: 20px 0;">
